 of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mulvaney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Brendan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilmheana</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Meana</i>’, a personal name which may be derived from <i>mion</i> ‘small thing’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulvenna","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish (Antrim): variant of   Mulvaney  ."]},{"name":"Mulvany","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Sean Patrick.","Irish: variant of   Mulvaney  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Mulvaney Watson was born about 1321, in Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, his father, Richard de Watson, was 52 and his mother, Ella Whitehurst, was 52. He married Isabella Campbell in 1359, in Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1387, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"Abt 1321–about 1387":"umbes 1321–umbes 1387","1321–1387":"1321–1387","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1321–1421":"1321–1421","1386–1460":"1386–1460","1270–1360":"1270–1360","1270–1355":"1270–1355","1460":"1460","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1359":"1359","Abt 1321":"umbes 1321","1355":"1355","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1387":"1387","1321":"1321","1386":"1386",